│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in                                 │
│ SCEVDbgValueBuilder::appendToVectors with assertion `!LocationOps.empty()`.   │
│ This means we attempted to append a salvage expression whose builder had no   │
│ location operands. The reproducer is a loop with a single dbg.value that      │
│ tracks a 128-bit induction-like PHI (start = large 128-bit constant, stride = │
│ 1). LSR's SCEV-based salvage logic tries to build a recovery expression for   │
│ the dbg.value after transformations. The dbg.value has an empty original      │
│ DIExpression (no ops), so SalvageDVI expects to fully replace it using a      │
│ constructed SCEVDbgValueBuilder. However, the builder was left empty,         │
│ triggering the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nDebug output shows: \n- │
│ IV SCEV: {0,+,1}\n- restore dbg.value to pre-LSR state\n- pre/post-LSR state  │
│ changed\n- salvaging location at index 0 with SCEV:                           │
│ {4704496199548239085565,+,1}\nImmediately after this, the pass crashes inside │
│ appendToVectors.\nThe large start constant (4704496199548239085565) exceeds   │
│ 64 bits (needs ~72 bits). The salvage mechanism attempts an offset-based      │
│ recovery first.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn SalvageDVI (lines ~6869-6875), │
│ the code does:\n```\nif (optional<APInt> Offset =                             │
│ computeConstantDifference(...)) {\n  if (Offset->getSignificantBits() <=      │
│ 64)\n    createOffsetExpr(...); // pushes location\n  // else do nothing\n}   │
│ else if (!createIterCountExpr(...)) return false;\n```\nWhen an offset exists │
│ but is wider than 64 bits, neither createOffsetExpr nor createIterCountExpr   │
│ is invoked. This leaves the freshly allocated SalvageExpr builder with empty  │
│ LocationOps. After the loop, for an originally empty DIExpression, code       │
│ assumes the builder exists and calls `appendToVectors`, asserting that        │
│ LocationOps contains the IV. The assertion fires because LocationOps is       │
│ empty. The intended logic was to fall back to iteration-count-based salvage   │
│ when offset-based salvage is inapplicable. That fallback only happens when no │
│ offset is computable, not when it is computable but unusable (>64 bits).      │
│ Hence builder remains empty and crash ensues.\n\n4. Proposed Edit             │
│ Points(s):\nEdit lines 6869-6873 in                                           │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopStrengthReduce.cpp to add a fallback when the  │
│ offset exists but is too wide. Replace:\n```\nif (std::optional<APInt> Offset │
│ =\n        SE.computeConstantDifference(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], SCEVInductionVar))   │
│ {\n  if (Offset->getSignificantBits() <= 64)\n                                │
│ SalvageExpr->createOffsetExpr(Offset->getSExtValue(), LSRInductionVar);\n}    │
│ else if (!SalvageExpr->createIterCountExpr(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], IterCountExpr,\n  │
│ SE))\n  return false;\n```\nwith:\n```\nif (std::optional<APInt> Offset =\n   │
│ SE.computeConstantDifference(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], SCEVInductionVar)) {\n  if      │
│ (Offset->getSignificantBits() <= 64) {\n                                      │
│ SalvageExpr->createOffsetExpr(Offset->getSExtValue(), LSRInductionVar);\n  }  │
│ else {\n    // Fallback: offset too large to encode directly, use iter-count  │
│ salvage.\n    if (!SalvageExpr->createIterCountExpr(DVIRec.SCEVs[i],          │
│ IterCountExpr, SE))\n      return false;\n  }\n} else if                      │
│ (!SalvageExpr->createIterCountExpr(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], IterCountExpr, SE)) {\n   │
│ return false;\n}\n```\nThis guarantees either offset salvage or               │
│ iteration-count salvage populates LocationOps, or we abort salvage early      │
│ before merge, preventing the assertion.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash results  │
│ from missing fallback logic when a computable offset is too wide (>64 bits).  │
│ Adding the fallback to attempt createIterCountExpr in that case ensures the   │
│ builder always has the IV location before appendToVectors is called, or the   │
│ salvage aborts safely. This prevents the assertion and allows loop-reduce to  │
│ proceed correctly for large (>64-bit) induction starts.\n"})                  │
