│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs in SCEVDbgValueBuilder::appendToVectors with assertion       │
│ `!LocationOps.empty()`. This means we attempted to append a salvage           │
│ expression whose builder had no location operands. The reproducer is a loop   │
│ with a single dbg.value that tracks a 128-bit induction-like PHI (start =     │
│ large 128-bit constant, stride = 1). LSR's SCEV-based salvage logic tries to  │
│ build a recovery expression for the dbg.value after transformations. The      │
│ dbg.value has an empty original DIExpression (no ops), so SalvageDVI expects  │
│ to fully replace it using a constructed SCEVDbgValueBuilder. However, the     │
│ builder was left empty, triggering the assertion.                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ Debug output shows:                                                           │
│ - IV SCEV: {0,+,1}                                                            │
│ - restore dbg.value to pre-LSR state                                          │
│ - pre/post-LSR state changed                                                  │
│ - salvaging location at index 0 with SCEV: {4704496199548239085565,+,1}       │
│ Immediately after this, the pass crashes inside appendToVectors.              │
│ The large start constant (4704496199548239085565) exceeds 64 bits (needs ~72  │
│ bits). The salvage mechanism attempts an offset-based recovery first.         │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In SalvageDVI (lines ~6869-6875), the code does:                              │
│ ```                                                                           │
│ if (optional<APInt> Offset = computeConstantDifference(...)) {                │
│   if (Offset->getSignificantBits() <= 64)                                     │
│     createOffsetExpr(...); // pushes location                                 │
│   // else do nothing                                                          │
│ } else if (!createIterCountExpr(...)) return false;                           │
│ ```                                                                           │
│ When an offset exists but is wider than 64 bits, neither createOffsetExpr nor │
│ createIterCountExpr is invoked. This leaves the freshly allocated SalvageExpr │
│ builder with empty LocationOps. After the loop, for an originally empty       │
│ DIExpression, code assumes the builder exists and calls `appendToVectors`,    │
│ asserting that LocationOps contains the IV. The assertion fires because       │
│ LocationOps is empty. The intended logic was to fall back to                  │
│ iteration-count-based salvage when offset-based salvage is inapplicable. That │
│ fallback only happens when no offset is computable, not when it is computable │
│ but unusable (>64 bits). Hence builder remains empty and crash ensues.        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ Edit lines 6869-6873 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LoopStrengthReduce.cpp to  │
│ add a fallback when the offset exists but is too wide. Replace:               │
│ ```                                                                           │
│ if (std::optional<APInt> Offset =                                             │
│         SE.computeConstantDifference(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], SCEVInductionVar)) {    │
│   if (Offset->getSignificantBits() <= 64)                                     │
│     SalvageExpr->createOffsetExpr(Offset->getSExtValue(), LSRInductionVar);   │
│ } else if (!SalvageExpr->createIterCountExpr(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], IterCountExpr,  │
│                                              SE))                             │
│   return false;                                                               │
│ ```                                                                           │
│ with:                                                                         │
│ ```                                                                           │
│ if (std::optional<APInt> Offset =                                             │
│         SE.computeConstantDifference(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], SCEVInductionVar)) {    │
│   if (Offset->getSignificantBits() <= 64) {                                   │
│     SalvageExpr->createOffsetExpr(Offset->getSExtValue(), LSRInductionVar);   │
│   } else {                                                                    │
│     // Fallback: offset too large to encode directly, use iter-count salvage. │
│     if (!SalvageExpr->createIterCountExpr(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], IterCountExpr,     │
│ SE))                                                                          │
│       return false;                                                           │
│   }                                                                           │
│ } else if (!SalvageExpr->createIterCountExpr(DVIRec.SCEVs[i], IterCountExpr,  │
│ SE)) {                                                                        │
│   return false;                                                               │
│ }                                                                             │
│ ```                                                                           │
│ This guarantees either offset salvage or iteration-count salvage populates    │
│ LocationOps, or we abort salvage early before merge, preventing the           │
│ assertion.                                                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash results from missing fallback logic when a computable offset is too │
│ wide (>64 bits). Adding the fallback to attempt createIterCountExpr in that   │
│ case ensures the builder always has the IV location before appendToVectors is │
│ called, or the salvage aborts safely. This prevents the assertion and allows  │
│ loop-reduce to proceed correctly for large (>64-bit) induction starts.        │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
